<h3 id="one-more-thing">One more thing&hellip;</h3>

<p>As a final and mostly unrelated aside, I have a cool setup for my work VPN. Cisco&rsquo;s AnyConnect VPN client makes accessing anything <em>not</em> on the VPN a pain, and it doesn&rsquo;t store passwords, so you have to constantly log in and out of the VPN and paste your password every time.</p>

<p>Instead I run a Docker container on my Mac mini server in the basement that&rsquo;s constantly logged into the VPN &mdash; but only for Oracle sites using an automatic proxy configuration it hosts &mdash; and tunnel a port from my various machines through that container&rsquo;s ports. So I&rsquo;m always on VPN, but also not. It&rsquo;s pretty cool.</p>
<div class="footnotes" role="doc-endnotes">
  <ol>
    <li id="fn:intel">
      <p>I need this machine mostly for app development. There&rsquo;s a weird bug in the old version of WebKit that crashes on print operations in Marked unless it&rsquo;s compiled on an Intel machine. It&rsquo;s so weird that even legends like Rich Siegel and Daniel Jalkut couldn&rsquo;t help me figure it out.&nbsp;<a href="https://brettterpstra.com#fnref:intel" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#8617;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:names">
      <p>I don&rsquo;t know why, but my machines are all named for horrible emotions. Agony, Misery, Despair, Doom&hellip; but my Mac mini is named &ldquo;Micro,&rdquo; the exception to the rule. I guess my Oracle laptop is another exception &ndash; it&rsquo;s obviously named &ldquo;Seer.&rdquo;&nbsp;<a href="https://brettterpstra.com#fnref:names" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#8617;</a></p>
    </li>
